We have recommended the following:

Enjoin the Municipal Social Welfare Development Officer to conduct verification on the eligibility of all the beneficiaries of the aforementioned financial assistance and prepare a duly certified list of Individuals belonging to the different Informal Sectors of the municipality and furnish the Municipal Accountant of the same as basis in identifying the ineligible beneficiaries;

Require the identified ineligible beneficiaries to refund the amount received and distribute the refunded amount proportionately to all other qualified beneficiaries;

Ensure that all financial assistance/fund transfers received in the future shall be spent only for the specific purpose for which the funds were received; and

Enjoin the Municipal Accountant to have a copy of all Memorandum of Agreement entered into by the LGU of Don Victoriano as basis for the disbursement of funds and for reference on evaluation of submitted liquidations.

We recommended to the management to:
Enjoin the Municipal Accountant to stop the granting of additional cash advance unless the previous cash advance given is first settled or proper accounting thereof is made;
Withhold the salaries of all accountable officers who are still connected with the LGU until settlement of their respective cash advances pursuant to Section 5.1.3 of COA Circular No. 97-002;
Send demand letters through a registered mail to those accountable officers who are not anymore connected with the LGU and/or cause the withholding of the amount due from the concerned officials and employees to compel them to settle their accounts. Management may resort to legal action if no settlement has been made after sending three (3) demand letters;
File a request for authority to write-off for the accounts that are deemed dormant and liquidation is futile, to be guided by the procedures contained in COA Circular 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016; and
Streamline the review process of Liquidation Reports taking into consideration the scope and purpose of a particular review to facilitate timely recording of liquidation of the cash advances.

We recommended to the management to:
Enjoin the Municipal Accountant to implement the accrual basis of recognizing revenue to conform with the International Public Sector Accounting Standards;
Direct the Municipal Treasury to maintain ledger cards to show the unpaid balance at any given time and other relevant data;
Exhaust remedies available to the Municipality in the collection of the delinquent accounts; and
Religiously follow the provisions in the Updated Municipal Revenue Code of the LGU.

We recommended to the management to:
Secure a duly approved amendments on the rental rates of the heavy equipment otherwise, impose the rates prescribed in the Updated Municipal Revenue Code;
Establish a sound and clear policies and procedures in renting out its heavy equipment taking into consideration the persons responsible from the preparation of lease contract up to the receipt of payment in order to attain the LGU’s target income from the lease of heavy equipment;
Ensure that all lease of heavy equipment are covered with written lease agreement with a fair and reasonable terms with due consideration of the Municipal Revenue Code;
Consider hiring of heavy equipment operators so that actual numbers of hours used shall be monitored and recorded accurately and proper equipment handling and maintenance can be imposed unto them;
Require the Equipment-In-Charge to prepare Monthly Report on Heavy Equipment Utilization and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant and the auditor; and
Enjoin the Treasury Office to prepare individual ledger cards for every lessee in order to monitor their billings and payments.

We recommended the following:
Create an inventory committee composed of adequate number of members with at least one member each from the Accounting Unit and Supply Unit and enjoin them to conduct the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts of the Municipality in accordance with the prescribed procedures embodied in COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability;
After the conduct of inventory taking, direct the inventory committee to prepare and submit the following to the Audit Team in the prescribed format:
Report on Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE);
Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP), if there are unserviceable properties found during inventory taking;
Request for Relief from Accountability by Accountable persons for lost PPE items under their accountability, if any;
Journal Entry Vouchers drawn by the Accounting Unit for recognition of loss of PPE from concerned accountable officers/personnel, if any, and other necessary adjusting entries;
Enjoin the Municipal Accountant to derecognize properties that do not qualify on the capitalization threshold of PPE and require the Supply Officer to prepare Inventory Custodian Slip (ICS) for each recorded PPEs that are to be derecognized from PPE account due to capitalization threshold of PPE and ensure that future issuances of semi-expandable properties are issued with ICS and Property Acknowledgement Receipt (PAR) for property and equipment;
Instruct the Supply Officer to prepare yearly report of inventory of semi-expandable properties in order to monitor existence of the said properties;
Secure a deed of donation for the donated lot and ambulance and ensure that future donations received by the LGU are covered with a deed of donation to protect the LGU’s right over the asset; and
Direct the Municipal Accountant to adjust the above-cited deficiencies on inventoriable items that were recorded as PPE and on the completed project that remained recorded as CIP.

We recommended to the management to:
Update the Annual Investment Plan through a revisit of the unimplemented development projects and review its viability and necessity, taking into considerations and strictly observing the guidelines set in DBM-DOF-DILG JMC No. 1 dated November 4, 2020, as well as other budgeting guidelines;
Identify and include only in the Annual Investment Plan of the LGU those programs, projects and activities that are implementable within the calendar year;
Transfer only to the Loan Amortization bank account the exact amount of loan amortization in order to refrain funds from being idle;
Require the MPDO to regularly monitor and evaluate the implementation of the projects and programs and to apprise the Municipal Budget Office for possible realignments. Ensure that excess appropriations from completed projects are realigned periodically;
Enjoin the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator and Municipal Budget Officer to have their own monitoring on the utilization 20% DF including the unexpended prior years’ balances; and
Direct the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the cash-in-bank balance with the unexpended balance of the 20% DF.

We recommended to the management to:
Establish a sound and clear policies and procedures in the distribution of fertilizers and collection thereat taking into consideration the person responsible from the preparation of promissory notes and acknowledgement receipts up to the receipt of payment in order to develop a strong internal control over the implementation of the program;
Enjoin the Municipal Agriculture Officer (MAO) to informatively explain the importance of promissory note to the corn farmers and ensure that future distribution of fertilizers is covered with signed promissory notes;
Instruct the MAO to reconcile the deficiencies noted on the reports submitted to Local COA in order to attain the correct balance of the collectibles and to fast track the collection of the receivables in order to achieve the objective of the program; and
Direct the Municipal Accountant to adjust the deficiencies noted on the recording of payment and the distribution of the fertilizers and to reconcile the recorded ‘Due to NGA’ account for fertilizer with the report of collection submitted by the MAO to reflect correct balances of the accounts.

We have recommended the following:

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare adjusting entries to record the accountabilities of the barangays in the books of the municipality by debiting the ‘Due from LGUs’ account and crediting the ‘Due to LGUs’ account for the amount released to the barangays which remain unliquidated;

Demand liquidation with complete supporting documents from the beneficiary barangays on the utilization of the funds received and provide the appropriate accounting entries thereof;

Ensure that the fund is duly covered with Memorandum of Agreement with the beneficiary barangays; and

Refrain from receiving financial assistance intended for its barangays, instead require the latter to enter into agreement with the source agency in the exercise of its local autonomy.

We have recommended the following:

Stop the practice of receiving funds for programs of which implementation extends beyond its territorial jurisdiction so as to allow other LGUs to enjoy genuine and meaningful local autonomy to enable them to attain their fullest development as self-reliant communities and make them more effective partners in the attainment of national goals;

Conduct verification on the suspected double claims and submit to the Auditor the result of validation with duly certified copies of valid identification cards;

Prohibit the transfer of cash advance from one Accountable Officer (AO) to another, instead designate a Special Disbursing Officer and ensure that the latter is duly bonded before assuming financial accountabilities; and

Submit the following documents immediately to avoid issuance of Notice of Suspension:

Approved Project Proposal accompanied with approved work program;
Certificate of Completion signed by the Department of Labor and Employment (DOLE RO-X); and
Liquidation report of the unliquidated cash advance amounting to ₱23,622,000.00 duly supported with the appropriate documentary requirements.

We have recommended the following:

Submit the following documents immediately to avoid issuance of Notice of Suspension:

A detail or information on how the savings was generated, as a result of cost-cutting and systems improvement measures, used as fund sources for the CNA Incentive are determined;

Proof of accomplishment of the LGU’s program/activities/projects approved in their LGU budget for FY 2020 as of September 30, 2020;

Written Resolution of the Employee Organization-Management Consultative Committee or a similar body composed of representatives from management and the negotiating agent in accordance with Item 5.1 of DBM Budget Circular No. 2020-5; and

Provide additional funding source for the ₱366,616.14 budget deficit, otherwise it shall be disallowed in audit.

Other recommendations were already fully implemented except for the following:

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to strictly implement the recording of Public Infrastructure accounts from the registry to the municipal books in consonance to the provisions of Section 3.7 of COA Circular 2016-004; 

Require the Municipal accountant to retrieve records of the unaccounted other infrastructure assets of the municipality;

Require the Municipal Engineer to conduct physical appraisal of all the infrastructure asset and submit the same to the municipal accountant for proper recording; and

